      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3173_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>

               <note rend="pencil" hand="other" style="text-orientation:sideways-right">
                  <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHenniker">Hon. Mrs Henniker</persName>
               </note>
               <address rend="letterhead">
                  <addrLine>13 Stratford Place, W.</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>TELEPHONE 3924 GERRARD</addrLine>
               </address>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1913-10-25">Oct 25.(13</date>
               </dateline>

               <salute>My dear friend:</salute>
            </opener>

            <p>Needless to say I was delighted to receive the book from you, with its charming
               inscription. Only <hi rend="underline">yesterday</hi> I read some very pleasant
               things about you &amp; it in "<orgName type="newspaper" ref="#ps:DailyMail"
                        ><choice><abbr>D</abbr><expan>Daily</expan></choice> Mail</orgName>" &amp;
                  "<orgName type="newspaper" ref="#ps:EveningStandard"
                        ><choice><abbr>Evg</abbr><expan>Evening</expan></choice> Standard</orgName>"
               – It must have been rather hard work to get it all put together? but I am sure dear
                  <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Miss Dugdale</persName> helped you very much. I
               shall write again &amp; tell you which stories appeal most to me. <persName
                  ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Miss
                     <choice><abbr>D.</abbr><expan>Dugdale</expan></choice></persName> will have
               given you my message of thanks for
                  <choice><abbr>yr</abbr><expan>your</expan></choice>
               <hi rend="underline">very</hi>
               <hi rend="underline">kind</hi> thought of asking me to stay &amp; see the play. But I
               am not going to any plays at present, &amp; on Monday return to my quiet little
               cottage in <!--Shoreham, Kent?--><placeName ref="#pl:ShorehamKent"
                  >Shoreham</placeName>, to superintend gardening operations. Some day I hope you
               will spare a day or two, to come &amp; see me there? <pb n="2"
                  facs="uoedh_hl_h.3173_2.jpg"/> It is a beautiful neighbourhood, full of interest
               of all kinds.</p>

            <p>I was at <placeName ref="#pl:Crewe">Crewe</placeName> about a week ago, &amp; among
               the guests was <persName ref="#ps:LordNewton">Lord Newton</persName>, who is as you a
               brilliant speaker, &amp; who has just published <persName ref="#ps:LordLyons">Lord
                  Lyons</persName>'s biography. He is an enthusiastic admirer of <hi
                  rend="underline">yours</hi>, (of "<ref target="#bib:Hardy1891_Tess">Tess</ref>", I
               gathered very especially.) That was the book he talked of. I can't help believing
               that it <hi rend="underline">is</hi>
               <choice><abbr>yr</abbr><expan>your</expan></choice> high water mark?</p>

            <p>I see you don't say in the preface to <choice><abbr>y<hi rend="superscript"
                        >r.</hi><expan>your</expan></abbr></choice> new book in what magazines the
               stories have appeared?</p>

            <p>I am going to send you a little book of verses by <persName
                  ref="#ps:MillicentWedmore">Miss Wedmore</persName>, which are really very good I
               think. You may find some in it that are sympathetic to you I hope.</p>

            <p>Best thanks again for the book – &amp; your kind thoughts.</p>

            <closer>
               <salute>Always <choice><abbr>yr</abbr><expan>your</expan></choice> friend</salute>
               <signed>FH.</signed>
            </closer>



         </div>
      </body>
   </text>
